  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass of ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a), you must first look up the atomic masses of each element that makes up the ammonium ion:\n\n1. **Nitrogen (N)**: The atomic mass of nitrogen is approximately 14.01 g/mol.\n2. **Hydrogen (H)**: The atomic mass of hydrogen is approximately 1.008 g/mol.\n\nAmmonium consists of one nitrogen atom and four hydrogen atoms. To calculate the molecular mass of NH\u2084\u207a, you can use the following steps:\n\n1. **Calculate the contribution from nitrogen**:\n   \\[\n   1 \\times \\text{Atomic mass of N} = 1 \\times 14.01\\, \\text{g/mol} = 14.01\\, \\text{g/mol}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Calculate the contribution from hydrogen**:\n   \\[\n   4 \\times \\text{Atomic mass of H} = 4 \\times 1.008\\, \\text{g/mol} = 4.032\\, \\text{g/mol}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Add the contributions together**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Molecular mass of NH\u2084\u207a} = 14.01\\, \\text{g/mol} + 4.032\\, \\text{g/mol} = 18.042\\, \\text{g/mol}\n   \\]\n\nTherefore, the molecular mass of the ammonium ion (NH\u2084\u207a) is approximately **18.04 g/mol**.",
